With same-sex marriages now set to resume in California, about 30 percent of Americans live in states where SSM is legal. Gay marriage isn't a change that's coming in the future, depending on how battles in the courts and at the ballot box turn out. It's a fait accompli. The bigger question isn't whether more states will recognize same-sex marriage—let alone whether there's much possibility of rollback—but on what the terms of victory of the SSM side is going to be consolidated. Conservatives have a different battle to fight, psychologically as well as legally, to preserve religious liberty and ensure that this revolution already made doesn't enter a more radical phase. High-strung right-wingers who say, for example,that the country might as well embrace polygamy if it's going to have same-sex marriage are not doing themselves any favors.
